 @milenatos  1. the attention span will not improve without practice and challenging  this limittion. It means absolutely nothing to the teacher. By breaking down content of the lesson, providing a good variety of tasks and chunking them you can keep attention of a hen for 2 hrs. 
2. No, older generations know much more facts than young one. Ask your parnets to name all continents or  list all countries starting with Z and they will recite you all you want. Young generation struggles to tell the difference between a city and a country. At least in the USA. The style of education has changed since our parents were at school, and while we rememebr a lot of factual content, students now don't know what to look for unless they are taught.
3. Tools are exactly that- a tool. A student who is taught at school how to use them, with background knowlede in subjects will be able to use them creatively. However, some people can't ever pick up a pencil and be creative, no matter what quality of tools will you provide. Simiralily, creative kid will take a lollipop stick and scratch a paint on the wall to release creativity there.... School must provide a challenge for those kids and make sure those less creative will also be ale to find their niche somewhere

